          <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: #52525b; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Fastest results. Catches within 24–48 hours with a good set.</p>
          <a href="/methods/victor-traps" class="btn">Victor Trap Guide</a>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e4e4e7; border-radius: 8px; background: #fafafa;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Bait Stations</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: #52525b; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Effective for larger infestations. Higher pet risk — read the guide first.</p>
          <a href="/methods/poison-bait-stations" class="btn">Bait Station Guide</a>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e4e4e7; border-radius: 8px; background: #fafafa;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Not Sure Where to Start?</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: #52525b; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Browse all 13 methods or take the 3-question quiz.</p>
          <a href="/methods" class="btn">All Methods</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">For gear, Mark's tested picks are in <a href="/traps">The Armory</a> — traps, probes, and the tools actually in rotation on real jobs.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What kind of soil do gophers prefer?</summary>
          <p>Gophers prefer loose, friable soil — sandy loam, well-amended garden beds, and recently tilled ground are ideal. Dense clay or compacted hardpan slows them down but doesn't stop them. Irrigated soil is especially attractive because consistent moisture keeps it workable year-round, even in dry climates.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do gophers follow irrigation lines?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Gophers follow moisture through soil, and irrigation creates a reliable wet corridor they use as a highway. Drip lines are especially vulnerable — gophers chew through emitters and tubing to reach moisture. If your gopher damage appears in a straight line running parallel to an irrigation run, that's almost certainly what's happening.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Are some plants more likely to attract gophers?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Gophers are drawn to anything with fleshy, tuberous, or starchy roots — dahlias, tulips, carrots, sweet potatoes, and most fruit trees are high-value targets. Dense lawn grass is also attractive because the thick root mat provides both food and tunnel cover. Daffodils are one of the few plants gophers consistently avoid.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Can I make my yard gopher-proof without trapping?</summary>
          <p>Not completely, but you can significantly reduce pressure. Underground hardware cloth barriers are the most effective passive defense — nothing gets through 1/2-inch galvanized mesh installed 18 inches deep with a 6-inch outward-facing lip. Swapping in gopher-resistant plants and fixing irrigation leaks also helps. But if you already have an active gopher, trapping is the only way to actually remove it.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

